Json and JPA annotations don&#39;t really interact with each other.  To JPA, you have an empty object that it doesn&#39;t know how to reference or interact with.

1) you need to make Trainer a top level class annotated with @Entity.  JPA says

&gt; &quot;The entity class must be a top-level class.&quot;

2) Trainer needs to have an ID of some sort.  otherwise ManyToOne won&#39;t be able to refer to it.

3) You will probably need a custom setter of some sort. Possibly:

&gt;     @JsonSetter(&quot;trainer)
&gt;     // assumes your ID is int or Integer
&gt;     public void setTrainerFromJson(Integer id) {
&gt;       if (id != null) {
&gt;          this.trainer = trainerRepository.findById(id);
&gt;       } else {
&gt;         this.trainer = null;
&gt;       }
&gt;     }

trainer can still be null if the trainer has not already been created, and you would need to inject the trainer repository into the client class (there may be timing issues during JPA scanning and creation)

